{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563380"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:57:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:57:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16752"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16752"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.04,0.59,0,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9443"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"2308"},{"type":"tags","id":"3233"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45317"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with an eight-hour history of progressive difficulty speaking and abnormal neck posturing. He reports jaw tightness and difficulty opening his mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a history of schizophrenia and was discharged from hospital one week ago after a prolonged admission. He received an intramuscular antipsychotic injection three days ago as part of his discharge plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history is otherwise unremarkable. His current medications are clozapine and sodium valproate. He does not take any other regular medications. There is no relevant social, occupation, or travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears anxious and oriented. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There are sustained contractions of his neck, jaw and truncal muscles with retrocollis and opisthotonus. Neurological examination shows generalised rigidity but normal power, reflexes and sensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal white cell count 12.2 \u00d7 10^9/L (4.0\u201311.0) and creatine kinase 850 U/L (40\u2013200).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin toxicity","Antipsychotic-induced acute dystonia","Convulsive status epilepticus","Stiff person spectrum disorder"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute dystonia is an extrapyramidal adverse effect due to dopamine receptor blockade, often emerging within hours to days of starting, increasing, or administering a long-acting antipsychotic. It presents with sustained, painful muscle contractions causing abnormal postures such as retrocollis, trismus and opisthotonus. The preserved consciousness, absence of fever, onset within days of an intramuscular antipsychotic, and focal sustained contractions point to \u003Cstrong\u003EAntipsychotic-induced acute dystonia\u003C/strong\u003E. Mild leucocytosis and moderately raised creatine kinase (CK) can be explained by muscle activity and stress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by hyperthermia, severe generalised rigidity, altered mental state and autonomic dysfunction, usually evolving over one to three days after dopamine blockade. CK is typically markedly elevated, often well above 1,000 U/L, and fever is expected. This patient is afebrile, oriented, and has only a moderate CK rise, making this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E features neuromuscular hyperactivity with inducible or spontaneous clonus, hyperreflexia (often greater in the lower limbs), agitation, diaphoresis and hyperthermia. Clozapine and sodium valproate are not typical precipitants, there is no clonus or hyperreflexia, and the pattern is of sustained dystonic posturing rather than tremor or clonus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConvulsive status epilepticus\u003C/strong\u003E would usually involve impaired awareness or postictal confusion, rhythmic motor activity, tongue biting, or incontinence. The sustained fixed postures with preserved orientation over hours and the examination showing normal power and reflexes argue against an ictal state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStiff person spectrum disorder\u003C/strong\u003E causes progressive axial rigidity and stimulus-sensitive spasms over months to years, often with hyperlordosis and gait impairment, not an acute onset over hours linked to antipsychotic exposure. The temporal profile and medication history do not fit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute dystonic reactions typically occur within hours to days of starting or increasing dopamine-blocking medication, including long-acting injections.","Key differentiators from life-threatening syndromes are preserved consciousness, focal sustained muscle contractions, and absence of hyperthermia.","Young men are at higher risk of antipsychotic-induced acute dystonia, especially with high-potency agents."],"references":["Campbell D. The management of acute dystonic reactions. Aust Prescr 2001;24:19-20.\rhttps://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2001.011","Dayalu P, Chou KL. Antipsychotic-induced extrapyramidal symptoms and their management. Expert opinion on pharmacotherapy. 2008 Jun 1;9(9):1451-62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94281"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16752"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94281"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-26T18:49:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-26T18:50:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9443"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112216"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"